<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 93 / Easter views dispel south-west's fear of false dawn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, WALES and WEST CORRESPONDENT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THE south-west the holiday weekend has largely borne out estate agents'
hopes that the recent signs of greater activity in the housing market would
not prove to be a false dawn.
Mr Michael Saunders, managing director of Fulfords, a south Devon chain of
26 offices, said: 'It is safe to say that we have had the busiest Easter
probably for five years.'
The picture varied across the region. Mr Saunders added: 'The general
perception is that we've turned the corner. We have had little peaks before
but it is continuing - and even more encouraging is that we are now selling
mid-range and more expensive houses again.'
One estate agent said it was a myth that Easter was a crucial time for the
property market, but the overall verdict was that the weekend had maintained
the more buoyant trend of the last three months. Agents spoke of prices
firming - especially at the lower end of the market - of a shortage of some
types of property, and of a renewed interest in holiday homes.
Mr John Smith is south-west director of Connells, with 10 offices including
Bristol, Bath, Chippenham and Swindon, which were open for all four days of
the holiday. 'We were very busy and all the signs are that the market is
carrying on as in the previous few months,' he said. Demand earlier in the
year was mostly from first-time buyers, now it was more evenly spread.
Another agent who reported an active Easter was Mr Dowell Conning,
south-west regional operations director of the Royal Life subsidiaries Allen
&amp; Harris and Gribble, Booth &amp; Taylor, which total 80 offices. He said: 'Good
Friday saw an unprecedented demand, certainly in recent times. There was
more interest, offers and positive response. Saturday was brisk but not so
busy.' He added: 'We have moved from amber to amber beige - not exactly 'go'
yet.
'The property market in my region started to decline in August 1988 and I'm
reluctant to sound too optimistic but I think we are now on our way. House
prices quarter on quarter have ceased to fall for the first time in five
years,' he said.
'There's no doubt in my mind that we have had continuous interest for some
time and in another month the market will have its own momentum - we're not
quite there yet.'
Mr Conning said buyers from London were emerging for village properties in
areas such as Devon.
