<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 93 / Hopes strengthen for housing upturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ESTATE AGENTS are more confident this year that Easter, traditionally the
start of the main house buying season, will confirm evidence of a sustained
recovery in one of the economy's worst-hit sectors.
The National Association of Estate Agents, which represents 10,000 member
companies, said yesterday that there was 'a different feel to the market'
this year after Easter optimism in each of the past two years rapidly turned
sour.
Mr Michael Jones, the association's president, said: 'Many of my colleagues
have had a lot of inquiries, especially from first-time buyers and at new
developments.'
Interest is reported to be strongest in the Midlands, Wales and the north,
but Mr Jones believed that London and the south-east would also 'gradually
feel the effect' of the recovery.
Estate agents and mortgage lenders announced figures which they claimed
proved the market was on the move after three years in the doldrums.
Royal Life Estates, which has nearly 500 estate agencies throughout the
country, said new instructions - a seller putting a property on the market -
and sales subject to contract were both up by a fifth in the last quarter.
Contracts exchanged were up by 40 per cent.
Mr Roger Hicklin, business development director, said: 'We are very cautious
about saying the worst is over, but the longer we have some stability with a
gentle upward trend in prices, then the more will confidence return.'
Abbey National, the country's second-largest mortgage lender, said mortgage
applications had doubled since March last year. Most of that rise had come
in the past three months, with a surge of 60 per cent between February and
March. At the same time the number of first-time buyers entering the market
had now risen to nearly 50 per cent of the total.
Halifax building society insisted there was 'no dramatic surge' in its 500
estate agencies over the weekend but there had been 'a healthy level' of
interest and inquiries.
