<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 93 / Ethics guidance for accountancy firms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACCOUNTANCY FIRMS will be required to provide more information to their
successors when a client changes advisers, according to draft guidelines
issued yesterday.
The revised guidance on changes in professional appointments comes from the
Chartered Accountants Joint Ethics Committee, which represents the three
chartered accountancy bodies covering the UK and Ireland.
It stresses that firms must provide minimum accounting information to a
successor even if disputes over fees remain outstanding.
The revised guidelines also emphasise that a change in a continuing
appointment is to be treated in the same way as a change in auditors. The
information a new firm should be told includes: reasons for a change;
disputes with the client over principle or practice; and any unlawful acts
or suspicions of fraud.
