<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 93 / Rush to join the Securities Institute: Number of
applications far exceeds estimates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY and RHODRI DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SURPRISINGLY high number, some 8,500 people, applied to join the new
Securities Institute during its first year of operation to March 31, far
exceeding the internal target of 5,500.
The institute's chief executive, Mr Tim Nicholson, said: 'There has been a
wall of application forms.'
It appears that about 3,500 applications flooded in during the final few
weeks as City securities industry professionals sought to take last-minute
advantage of a 'window of opportunity'.
Established practitioners applying up to March 31 were offered membership on
the basis only of regulatory checks and, in some cases, interviews. Full
membership will now only be granted to those who pass examinations lasting
nine hours.
The institute was set up last year after the Stock Exchange ended its
facility for personal membership. Its aim is to promote professional
standards and ethics, which have been under pressure in the securities
industry is some respects since the Stock Exchange's 'Big Bang' in 1986.
Members may adopt the initials MSI on business cards and letterheads.
About 4,600 applications have come from the 5,000 former members of the
Stock Exchange. The nearly 4,000 other applications suggests the new
association will embrace a wider professional community.
The institute was successful in attracting interest from practitioners in
areas such as investment management, corporate finance and futures trading.
Individuals from many national and regional law firms have applied, along
with accountancy and investment bankers, including some from Hill Samuel and
Samuel Montagu.
'The securities trade has always lacked an effective focal point,' said Mr
Nicholson. 'We are bridging the gap and the trade is responding. We have the
Law Society and Institute of Chartered Accountants, now the securities
industry is getting the representation it deserves.'
Unqualified applicants hoping to gain membership before examinations become
compulsory faced a torrid time negotiating the rigorous admissions criteria.
A strict membership system will include an eight-page application form,
detailed references from institute members or the directors of the
applicant's firm, and thorough regulatory checks.
Mr Nicholson accepts there will be some disreputable applicants: 'We will be
looking for individuals with substance. Almost half of these 'outside'
applicants will be interviewed to check their credentials.'
With headquarters next to the Monument in the City, the institute is forming
18 branches in the UK and offshore.
</TEXT>
