<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 93 / Political Notebook: The view from the trenches
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT IS back to the trenches. MPs returning to Westminster today after the
Easter break will find the contours of the battlefield have scarcely
changed. The Commons battle over the Maastricht treaty and the economy's
slow emergence from recession will continue to shape the political
landscape.
The next three months, parliament's summer term, will be no less critical
for that. They should show whether retreat has become a way of life for Mr
John Major's government. They should reveal whether Mr John Smith's Labour
party can find ammunition more lethal than the worthy respectability of its
leader.
Between now and July the prime minister must make up his mind whether to
give a fresh face to a weary-looking government with an extensive cabinet
reshuffle. Mr Smith must decide whether a solid public image and a sharp
Commons debating style provide sufficient substitute for the radicalism
demanded by some of his colleagues.
There will be a chance for the electorate to give their interim judgment.
Some 25m adults are eligible to vote in next month's county council
elections. In Newbury Mr Major will face the first by-election of the
parliament.
The local and by-election results will be brushed aside by the losers as
inconsequential to the long-term political fortunes of the participants. But
the results will have an important impact on the psychology of the
politicians.
A government as battered as the present one cannot lose in its electoral
heartland and expect its already ragged backbenchers to keep their nerve. Mr
Paddy Ashdown's Liberal Democrats have drifted on the sidelines since last
April. A strong showing in the local polls and victory in Newbury would put
them back in the political fight.
Everything hinges on Maastricht, of course. The return of the Maastricht
legislation to the Commons tomorrow will mark the opening of the final
chapter in this particular saga. No-one can predict with certainty the
denouement.
Ministers are upbeat. About 90 per cent of the hundreds of proposed
amendments have now been debated. Most of the government's other
legislation, including hefty bills on education, employment and leasehold
reform have been dealt with. Assuming that the Danes vote 'Yes' in their
second referendum next month, the odds are that the treaty will be ratified
by the end of July.
Mr Major cannot rest easy. His party's fifth columnists have become totally
detached from his leadership in their opposition to the treaty. There
remains a small but real chance that the arcane procedures of the Commons
may facilitate an amendment to incorporate the social chapter. If that
happened for the prime minister all would be lost.
The mood over Europe - and most else - will in turn be conditioned by the
economy. The Treasury is convinced that recovery is under way. Disgruntled
Conservative MPs want to see the green shoots flower before deciding that
the government has restored a grip on economic management.
As with Maastricht, Mr Major cannot afford to be wrong this time. No-one
expects recession to be followed by boom. But without strong and steady
confirmation of recovery he cannot begin to restore his authority.
The economy colours everything. With recovery underway the latest dispute
over testing in schools is likely to prove awkward but manageable. If the
economic indicators turn down again, the row could spark yet another
backbench rebellion.
There are other potential minefields. Unemployment is still rising. This
summer's public-spending round will be bloodier than most realise. The
fundamental review of Whitehall budgets being undertaken by Mr Michael
Portillo, the chief secretary, will remind Tory MPs how much easier it is to
talk about saving public money than it is to do it.
So there will be no shortage of targets for the opposition parties. And yet
Labour MPs are far from reassured. Mr Smith has a notional opinion poll lead
of 15 points but this appears to owe much more to the government's
unpopularity than to positive enthusiasm for a Labour alternative.
Mr Smith, a cautious, patient man cannot wait indefinitely before defining
that alternative. He must make up his mind about electoral reform, about his
party's links with the trades unions, and about the balance in its policies
between egalitarianism and individual opportunity.
Until then Labour, like the Tories, cannot expect to break out from its
trenches.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
