FT  14 APR 93 / Bristol prison facilities criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CARE of seriously disturbed inmates at Bristol prison remained
'dangerous and unacceptable' in spite of redevelopment work after riots
three years ago, Judge Stephen Tumim, chief inspector of prisons, said
yesterday.
More than Pounds 1m of damage was caused at Bristol during the riots that
swept British jails in the spring of 1990. The prison has since been
renovated at a cost of Pounds 3.5m.
In his latest report Judge Tumim says little appears to have changed apart
from the redevelopment work.
He refers to 'considerable achievements' in repairing the riot damage and
building relationships between prisoners and staff but says Bristol remains
a 'busy, overcrowded prison offering few facilities for inmates'.
The government says measures have already been taken to meet many of the
recommendations in Judge Tumim's report.
