<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 93 / Domestic air travel shows increase of 5.5%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN and ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DOMESTIC AIR travel showed its sharpest rise for more than a year during
March, indicating greater confidence among UK businesses which buy most of
the tickets for internal flights.
The latest traffic figures from BAA, which operates London's airports and
three in Scotland, show a 5.5 per cent year-on-year increase in domestic
passenger traffic.
The last time such a rise was recorded, in February last year, it was
attributed to a bounce back from the depressed figures of two years ago in
the aftermath of the Gulf war. Without the Gulf war effect, March showed the
biggest rise since August 1990.
The recovery in traffic echoes mild optimism in some quarters of the airline
industry. Many airlines operating across the North Atlantic, for example,
have increased capacity by more than 10 per cent for the summer season.
BAA's former chairman Sir Norman Payne believes the traffic growth on the
busy London-Edinburgh route closely fitted the trend in Britain's gross
domestic product.
But British Airways damped hopes that domestic traffic was recovering
sharply. It said the domestic travel business was 'still broadly depressed'.
Traffic from BAA airports to the rest of Europe increased more quickly than
domestic traffic, rising 9.6 per cent over March 1992.
The upward trend has been established for many months but may also be a
reflection of increased business done as a result of the European Community
single market which began on January 1.
Much of the gain was at the expense of short-haul charter traffic, down 4.2
per cent. This may have been a consequence of the modest fare cuts that some
of Europe's scheduled airlines introduced in the wake of the EC's partial
liberalisation of air traffic.
Stansted, London's loss-making third airport, continued to struggle to
establish itself as an alternative to Heathrow and Gatwick. While passenger
traffic grew by 5.7 per cent, the number of aircraft take-offs fell 8.3 per
cent.
Robert Taylor writes: There are no signs of any real recovery in the British
printing industry, according to the quarterly survey by the British Printing
Industries Federation. Only 10 per cent of its sample of companies enjoyed
an improvement in their trading conditions between mid-December and
mid-March, compared with 34 per cent who had expected them to be better.
The survey says: 'There have been too many false dawns and withered green
shoots to allow printers to be positively cheerful. Companies are chary too,
simply because they can detect little in the way of real confidence among
their customers or in the economy at large.'
</TEXT>
