<DATELINE>
   HANOI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Vietnam yesterday flatly rejected a report suggesting that it lied over the
number of American prisoners it was holding shortly before the US withdrawal
from Indochina in 1973, Reuter reports from Hanoi. It also denied it was
still holding any prisoners.
The issue, which flared up with disclosure of a document found in Moscow
archives and said to be from the North Vietnamese army, looked likely to
delay efforts to reconcile Hanoi and Washington 18 years after the Vietnam
war ended. Vietnamese officials said every time a breakthrough appeared
imminent in relations with the US, forces in Washington opposed to
reconciliation threw a spanner in the works.
