<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 93 / South Africa braced for mass strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH AFRICA was braced for potential violence during today's planned mass
strike called by the African National Congress to mourn the weekend
assassination of guerrilla leader Mr Chris Hani.
Mr Nelson Mandela, ANC president, warned last night on national television
that South Africa was 'on the brink of disaster'. In an emotional address,
he appealed for calm and urged respect for whites. 'We must not let the men
who worship war and who lust after blood precipitate actions that will
plunge our country into another Angola,' he said.
Mr Mandela issued a special appeal to South Arica's ultra-radical youth:
'You have lost a great hero. You have repeatedly shown that your love of
freedom is greater than. . . life itself. But you are the leaders of
tomorrow. Your country, your people, your organisation need you to act with
wisdom.'
He said Mr Hani would be buried on Monday, in one of the most important
political events in South African history. Constitutional talks would be
delayed by one week of mourning. Worried by the risk of violence, the South
African Chamber of Business (Sacob), the largest employer organisation,
issued an unusally conciliatory statement urging employers to handle the
tense situation with sensitivity. A Sacob official urged no disciplinary
action be taken against employees failing to attend work.
the organisation said, pointing out that the stayaway could mean employees
would be unable to attend work for lack of transport.
Yesterday, the first day of the ANC's planned campaign of 'rolling mass
action' passed off with some incidents of violence, especially in the
eastern Cape province where three youths were killed after they stoned a
police vehicle. Many parts of the province were declared 'unrest areas,'
with curfews and a ban on weapons.
A small demonstration was held outside the Boksburg magistrate's court where
the alleged assassin, Mr Janusz Walus, appeared. He was remanded in custody
until May 12. In another South African court, charges were withdrawn against
27 of 74 men accused of involvement in last year's Boipatong massacre, which
led to a nine-month suspension of constitutional talks.
</TEXT>
