<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 93 / Report to veto big reforms of ERM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR central bankers and treasury officials from the European Community
yesterday finished their report on the workings of the European exchange
rate mechanism after a 12-hour meeting.
Members of the EC monetary committee, meeting in Brussels, refused to give
details but confirmed that their analysis and recommendations would be
presented to Community finance ministers at a three-day informal council in
Kolding, Denmark, at the end of May.
'All's well that ends well,' said the Bank of England representative, Mr
Andrew Crockett, as he left the meeting.
The committee was asked to examine the workings of the exchange rate grid
following last September's currency crisis, during which both sterling and
the lira were forced out of the ERM.
Yesterday's meeting was held, as always, in secret, but the committee is
expected to recommend that there should be no fundamental reform of the
system - in spite of calls from member states, notably Britain, that alleged
'fault-lines' in the ERM should be treated.
Instead, the monetary experts believe existing rules - for example, those
which allow for more frequent technical realignments of European currencies
 -should be applied more strictly, and earlier, to avoid speculative
pressure on member currencies.
</TEXT>
