<HEADLINE>
FT  14 APR 93 / Rise in confidence lifts hopes of upturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK can look forward to an early economic recovery as sales and new order
books pick up and companies hire more staff, a business confidence survey
says today.
Dun &amp; Bradstreet, the business information company, reports that six out of
10 businesses expect sales to increase in the second quarter, against only
two expecting them to fall. The findings are significantly more optimistic
than in the previous quarter and will add to a growing impression that the
economy has reached a turning-point.
House prices have perked up recently, while car registrations for the first
quarter rose sharply compared with the same period last year. Meanwhile,
domestic air travel showed its steepest rise for more than a year during
March, indicating greater confidence among UK businesses which buy most of
the tickets for internal flights.
The latest traffic figures from the BAA, which operates London's airports
and three in Scotland, show a 5.5 per cent increase in domestic passenger
traffic last month compared with March 1992. Heathrow airport showed the
biggest gain in the south with an 8.3 per cent year-on-year rise in total
passengers to 3.8m last month. On the foreign exchanges the pound was
stronger against the D-Mark, closing 1 1/4 pfennigs higher at DM2.4625. In
New York, it finished at DM2.46025. Share prices were also more buoyant. The
FT-SE 100 index of leading shares rose 25 to 2,846.8.
Dun &amp; Bradstreet, which interviewed just under 2,000 managing directors
between March 17 and 31, reported that expectations about employment have
improved. More companies nationwide plan to hire staff than to fire them,
with optimism particularly high in London, the south-east, the east, Wales
and the north. The outlook is brightest in the service sector, with 35 per
cent reporting an intention to hire more staff against 19 per cent expecting
to cut back.
Although pressures on prices remain weak, the survey suggested that the
deflationary momentum of the economy was slowing. A higher proportion of
companies than in the previous quarter plan to pass on price increases to
customers, according to the survey. Half the companies, however, expect to
hold prices at last year's levels.
Official figures yesterday confirmed that producer price inflation remains
subdued although the effects of sterling's devaluation are continuing to put
pressure on manufacturers.
The Central Statistical Office reported that in March the prices of
manufactured goods leaving UK factories rose a seasonally adjusted 0.7 per
cent on the month. This left the annual rate of increase unchanged at 3.7
per cent. However, raw materials and fuel prices rose by 8.3 per cent in the
year to March, the highest rate of increase since July 1987.
The biggest jump in optimism was recorded among businesses in the service
sector. The optimism index, the percentage of respondents forecasting an
increase in sales minus the percentage expecting a decrease, leapt from 25
to 52. Confidence in the construction sector also rose.
Air travel grows, Page 8
Factory price rises, Page 10
