<HEADLINE>
FT  13 APR 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Further decline in bond
yields lifts equities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
ANOTHER big decline in bond yields, earned in the wake of more good
inflation news, lifted US share prices across the board yesterday, writes
Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 31.61 at 3,428.09,
near its high for the day. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500
ended up 6.12 at 447.96, while the Amex composite finished 1.84 higher at
418.08 and the Nasdaq composite up 6.79 at 673.12. Trading volume on the
NYSE was 260m shares.
Equity investors drew strength from the fixed-income markets, where last
Friday's news of a 0.1 per cent increase in March consumer prices prompted
heavy buying. The benchmark 30-year government bond rose sharply, pushing
the yield down to 6.79 per cent.
Two weeks ago yields were heading beyond 7 per cent on fears of revived
inflation. Stock markets were worried that this might hinder economic
recovery. In the last week, however, good news on consumer and producer
prices has seen yields retreat convincingly.
Enthusiasm was tempered, however, by concern about the approaching reporting
season. A handful of companies has already posted first-quarter earnings,
but until a fuller picture of corporate profitability, investors will remain
cautious.
Among individual stocks, banks were firmer in the wake of lower interest
rates. Chemical rose Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 42 3/8 , Chase Manhattan
firmed Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 36 5/8 , First Chicago rose Dollars 1 1/4 to
Dollars 43 7/8 , BankAmerica added Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 52 1/2 and Banc
One rose Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 60.
General Motors fell Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 39 1/8 in busy trading as
investors responded to Friday's news that a preliminary National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration inquiry had found safety defects in GM pickup
trucks built with 'side-saddle' fuel tanks. GM argued that its trucks were
built to federal safety standards, and denied the administration's request
that the company recall all 4.7m of the trucks built between 1973 and 1987.
On the Nasdaq market, Intel jumped Dollars 4 1/2 to Dollars 117 1/2 in heavy
trading after it reported strong first-quarter profits.
Canada
TORONTO closed higher in quiet trading. The TSE-300 index rose 23.21 points
to close at 3615.01 in volume of 40.3m shares. Trading value was CDollars
345.8m.
South Africa was closed for a public holiday.
