<HEADLINE>
FT  13 APR 93 / International Company News: Intel buoyed by exceptionally
strong first term
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTEL yesterday consolidated its position as the world's leading computer
chip maker with exceptionally strong first-quarter earnings and revenues on
the back of brisk sales of PCs using its microprocessors.
The unexpectedly robust results, and a bullish forecast for the second
quarter, lifted shares across the semiconductor manufacturing sector. Intel
firmed Dollars 4 1/2 to close at Dollars 117 1/2 , Motorola climbed Dollars
2 to a 52-week high of Dollars 70 3/8 and Advanced Micro Devices hit a
year-high of Dollars 25 3/4 , up Dollars  3/4 .
For the three months to March 27, Intel posted net profits of Dollars
547.9m, or Dollars 2.48 a share, on revenues of Dollars 2.02bn. This
compares with earnings of Dollars 184.1m, or 86 cents, on revenues of
Dollars 1.24bn a year earlier.
Wall Street had expected Intel to report earnings of about Dollars 2.13 a
share, and few analysts had expected per-share earnings to exceed Dollars
2.40.
Mr Andrew Grove, chief executive, said: 'It took us 22 years to get to the
Dollars 1bn a quarter in revenues and, thanks to the explosion in demand for
the Intel 486 chip, less than three years to get to Dollars 2bn a quarter.'
Intel is the leading supplier of microprocessor chips which form the brains
of more than 70 per cent of the world's PCs.
The company recently unveiled plans to add a Dollars 1bn expansion to its
New Mexico plant.
MOTOROLA, the US electronics manufacturer, also exceeded expectations by
posting 63 per cent improvement in underlying first quarter earnings to
Dollars 204m, or 75 cents a share, on sales which rose 19 per cent to
Dollars 3.63bn.
Wall Street had expected earnings of 64 cents a share. A year earlier,
Motorola reported underlying earnings of Dollars 125m, or 47 cents, on sales
of Dollars 3.05bn. A change in accounting standards reduced last year's net
income to Dollars 2m, or 1 cent a share.
</TEXT>
