<HEADLINE>
FT  13 APR 93 / Prison officers back Strangeways bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRISON OFFICERS at Strangeways, Manchester, have agreed to limit their right
to take industrial action in an attempt to keep the management of the prison
in the public sector.
Rival bids from the public and private sectors to run the rebuilt
Strangeways, severely damaged in riots three years ago, will be submitted to
the Home Office today.
The public sector bid will contain a procedural agreement between the Prison
Officers Association (POA) at Strangeways and the present prison management.
It guarantees that if the bid succeeds, standards set out in the management
contract with the government would be maintained during industrial action.
This would rule out all-out strikes and other highly disruptive forms of
industrial action.
Ministers have in the past characterised the POA as a militant trade union
that has resisted change in the prison service. POA members at Manchester
hope to prevent this reputation becoming a barrier to the public sector bid
succeeding.
Wolds, Britain's first privately managed prison, opened on Humberside last
year and the new Blakenhurst, in Hereford and Worcester, will open under
private management soon. The contract to run Strangeways - part of the
government's programme of market testing public services - is, however, the
first time the public and private sectors have bid against each other to
manage a prison.
The public sector bid to retain management of Strangeways is expected to
face competition from about five private sector bids, with a final decision
in midsummer.
The deadline for Strangeways bids comes at an awkward moment for ministers
in terms of another element of the policy to open up the criminal justice
system to the private sector - private management of court escort services.
Four prisoners escaped or were wrongly released last week during the first
few days of privately managed escort duties by Group 4 Court Services.
Group 4, which also manages Wolds prison, said it released one of the
prisoners on the orders of a court. It is to meet the director general of
the Prison Service to discuss the situation.
Conservative backbenchers are concerned that further escapes might embarrass
ministers over plans to extend the scheme.
Staff seek to capture Strangeways, Page 10
</TEXT>
