<HEADLINE>
FT  13 APR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two unusually tempting offers, and both at 9.00. Channel 4's excellent
catch-all culture series Without Walls shows the first of three programmes
on technological advances this century and asks the old Frankenstein
question: will mankind's ingenuity produce technology to serve our interests
or will it take over the world. Artificial intelligence, robotics and
plastic surgery all come into the picture. The movie Broadcast News,
receiving its first screening on terrestrial television (9.00 ITV), is
wickedly accurate and the funniest Hollywood film about television. It
involves romance and has a 'Thirty-something' flavour, but it is the
authentic and hilarious newsroom scenes which are so rewarding. Assignment
(7.45 BBC2) reports on the astounding political situation in Italy where
scores of politicians, civil servants and businessmen are now in prison. As
they await investigation for corruption the horrors of prison life are
inducing many to sing like canaries, producing a virtuous circle of
revelation and further incrimination.
</TEXT>
