<DOCNO>FT932-15532</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DDMB0ABWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930413
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 APR 93 / Management (The Growing Business): Closer UK/US links
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK government has launched a programme to help medium-sized British
companies establish alliances with similar US companies.
The three-year pilot programme is intended to help companies, which are
already exporting to the US, establish closer links by means of joint
product development, franchising, collaborative marketing and licensing
agreements.
The Strategic Alliance Service forms part of a broader Department of Trade
and Industry programme, called North America Now, which was launched last
month. The service* will be managed by accountants Price Waterhouse.
The new initiative is aimed at companies with turnover of between Pounds 5m
and Pounds 50m and employing between 50 and 500 people. Both independent
companies and subsidiaries of larger groups are eligible.
The DTI estimates that up to 1,500 UK companies will meet its criteria,
although it expects to sign up only 50 for the programme each year. Of these
it expects between 10 and 15 will find partners. These targets are modest,
the DTI acknowledges, but if successful the programme could be extended to
other markets.
Partnerships represent a less risky way into the US market than acquisitions
or setting up from scratch and tie up less capital. The economic climate and
the dollar/sterling exchange rates are also favourable, the DTI says.
The DTI will spend Pounds 185,000 a year on the programme while the cost to
companies which pass through all stages of the scheme and find a partner
will be Pounds 14,000 plus travel and other expenses.
Profiles of UK companies which meet the programme's criteria and which can
show they are committed to establishing US links will be matched with US
counterparts through Price Waterhouse's network of US offices.
UK companies will be provided with a shortlist of possible US partners and
meetings will be arranged. From then on it is up to the two companies to
negotiate a deal, the DTI says.
*Contact Price Waterhouse, Milton Gate, 1 Moor Lane, London EC2Y 9PB. Tel.
071 939 3000.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7363 Help Supply Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>COMP  Strategic links &amp; Joint venture.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 11
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT932-15533</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DDMB0ABVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930413
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 APR 93 / Engineering study dents theory of job flexibility
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TECHNICAL innovation and accelerating international competitive pressures
have not brought greater job flexibility and de-skilling to Britain's
engineering industry over the past 10 years, a survey published by Lancaster
University's engineering industry research group shows.
This contradicts the fashionable theory of the 'flexible' company with a
small core of full-time workers and an increasingly peripheral workforce
doing contracted-out work.
The broad-based survey of 148 engineering establishments, with half
employing fewer than 100 workers, found that there had been no increase in
the use of part-time employment in production.
This was not even the case in cleaning and catering. The survey argues that
instead of contracting more and more work, the engineering industry 'has
increasingly come to be characterised by technologically sophisticated,
increasingly skilled, full-time employment patterns during the last decade'.
It found that there was increased training of workers to cover other jobs,
more individualised forms of pay and increased shift work. Nearly three
quarters of the companies covered also introduced important technological
changes in their production processes.
The author, Mr Roger Pen, argues that the dominant trend in British
engineering has been 'an increasing reliance' on full-time workers.
'In British engineering plants during the 1980s the core workforce became
more and more the entire workforce,' he says.
The survey also found that 65.8 per cent of the sample had recognised unions
bargaining collectively. Half the unionised plants covered white-collar as
well as manual workers.
About 60 per cent of engineering plants reported no changes in the level of
union influence over either pay or work organisation.
Just more than half the plants had introduced new forms of worker
involvement during the 1980s, such as works councils, team briefings and
other forms of open communication. Profit sharing was virtually
non-existent, however, and quality circles were rare.
Changing Patterns of Work in the Contemporary Engineering Industry,
Department of Sociology, Lancaster University, Lancaster LA1 4YL. Pounds 50.
</TEXT>
