FT  13 APR 93 / BR in talks to avert strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FURTHER TALKS are to be held today between British Rail and the two main
rail unions in a final attempt to avert Friday's planned 24-hour stoppage,
Robert Taylor writes.
BR management worked over the holiday weekend to try to convince the unions
not to proceed with their planned disruption. The two sides, however, appear
far apart.
The RMT, the main rail union, continues to insist that it needs a guarantee
from BR of no future compulsory redundancies and an end to contracting-out
of work.
Aslef, the train drivers' union, is demanding that existing national
agreements covering the deployment of its members should not be changed.
Until now BR has tried to offer the unions forms of words that would
convince them that every effort would be made to avoid any compulsory
redundancies as the railway network prepared for privatisation, due to start
next year. But BR management failed on Friday to make any breakthrough with
the unions.
Sir Bob Reid, BR's chairman, has emphasised that the industry cannot afford
any more one-day strikes. The 24-hour stoppage by the RMT on April 2 cost BR
Pounds 10m gross.
