<HEADLINE>
FT  13 APR 93 / Staff seek to capture Strangeways: Public-sector bid to run
the recently modernised Manchester prison
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN the three years since the near destruction of Strangeways prison in
Manchester during the most serious prison riots of recent times, it has been
completely rebuilt and modernised within its Victorian red-brick shell.
Today the physical reconstruction will be followed by an equally remarkable
transformation of the management of Strangeways, when the public and private
sectors submit rival bids to run the prison.
Two private-sector companies have already been awarded contracts to manage
British prisons. But Strangeways - with accommodation for 1,150 men - is on
a bigger scale and, for the first time, the state prison service and the
private sector are bidding against each other as part of the government's
market testing of public services.
About six private-sector bids are expected. One from the Strangeways
management and staff led by Mr Robin Halward, the governor, will be pitched
against them. Mr Halward, former governor of Armley prison, Leeds, moved to
Strangeways last year to prepare the public-sector bid.
When Mr Halward's bid reaches the Home Office today it will emphasise that
it has the strong support of the Strangeways unions and staff. The Prison
Officers' Association and other prison-service unions are opposed to market
testing and private management. They decided, however, that rather than
boycott the process their strongest position was to demonstrate that the
public sector could compete and win.
Two members of the Strangeways POA committee have worked full-time on the
bid for the past six months as representatives of the unions and junior
staff.
The 400 Strangeways staff - almost all of whom experienced the 1990 riots -
are backing the bid even though they know that success would cost some of
them their jobs.
Mr Halward admitted: 'Staffing levels under our bid would be substantially
leaner than if the prison ser-vice had reopened Strange-ways in the
traditional way.'
Other concessions have been made. The POA has a reputation for traditional,
old-fashioned militancy. While Mr Halward believes the view of the prison
service as a 'dispute-ridden, industrial-relations dominated organisation'
is distorted, he has secured local POA agreement to maintain the prison's
contract with the government in the event of industrial action.
'No workforce can guarantee that there will never be a dispute of one sort
or another,' he said. 'But the bid will include a procedural agreement with
the local POA which guarantees the maintenance of standards required in the
service level agreement (the government contract) during any collective
dispute that there might be.'
The Strangeways staff bid also proposes a more devolved management structure
than in other state prisons.
Mr Halward said that historically the prison service had been 'full of the
Civil Service tradition' of concentrating on processes rather than outcomes.
'Until a few years ago work on suicide prevention in prison focused more on
being able to defend the prison service if a prisoner took his own life than
on looking at why it happened.
'We have to put judgment more to the fore by deciding what we want to
achieve and allowing managers at every level, within guidelines, to make
their own professional judgments about how to achieve it. Our bid proposes
more managerial devolution than is normal in a public prison, with managers
working out with their staff how to achieve objectives.'
Serious overcrowding, leading to prisoners being required to share cells for
most of the day, helped provoke the Strangeways riots. In the new
Strangeways men will be out of their cells for up 12 to 15 hours.
'But it is no use unlocking prisoners and then leaving them milling around
all day,' Mr Halward said.
'We have to try to get prisoners to indulge in positive activities, and
create a positive, active community in the hope that people might carry over
some of these values when they are released. Compared with other local
prisons, our bid proposes a much better programme of work, training,
education and ways of addressing offending behaviour,' he added.
The 350 prisoners who remained in Strangeways during rebuilding were
consulted when the bid was being prepared. Mr Halward believes in the need
to involve prisoners, but stressed: 'This is not going to be a democracy. We
would not be discharging our responsibility to the public if we just allowed
prisoners to do what they wanted.'
Bids to manage Strangeways will be reduced to a shortlist next month, with
the contract awarded in the summer. Staff at Strangeways would be
disappointed - and surprised - if their bid did not make the shortlist and
believe they have a real hope of winning.
Mr Halward said: 'We are convinced that the public sector bid is
commercially competitive. And one of our particular strong points is that we
have the workforce - the prison's highly experienced staff have agreed to
accept change, know what is expected of them, and are ready to deliver it.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
