<HEADLINE>
FT  13 APR 93 / Banks face severe losses on property: Shortfall of Pounds
8bn on loans in south-east estimated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANKS FACE a potential shortfall of more than Pounds 8bn on loans made for
office property in London and the south-east, says a report.
Estimates by St Quintin, a firm of chartered surveyors, illustrate the
severity of the banks' property losses, which resulted from the sharp rise
in bank lending to the property sector in the late 1980s and the subsequent
collapse in commercial property val-ues.
The firm believes that the Pounds 24.6bn of loans to London and south-east
offices may be secured on property worth just Pounds 16.4bn. In the central
London office sector, the worst-hit part of the market, loans of Pounds
10.8bn may be supported by assets worth only Pounds 6.4bn.
Mr Peter Damesick, a director of St Quintin, said the banks' losses might
not, however, be as large as the gap between the value of a loan and the
underlying asset.
In some cases the loans are guaranteed by other assets. Moreover, property
values may have risen by the time a loan matures.
Mr Damesick said: 'The shortfall between asset values and outstanding debts
can be expected to narrow as currently vacant buildings are gradually let
and values generally improve over the medium term.'
The report estimates that the Pounds 37.9bn of loans extended to the entire
UK commercial property sector is secured against property that has fallen in
value from Pounds 50.5bn to Pounds 31bn during the past four years.
The value of bank-financed property in the industrial and provincial office
markets has not, in aggregate, fallen below the outstanding debt.
The report says that one result of the fall in asset values to just more
than 80 per cent of the total debt is that institutional investors have less
to fear from the apparent debt mountain than is sometimes assumed.
Moreover, the quality of much of the bank-financed property stock is not of
institutional quality.
'Institutional investors have less to fear from the apparent debt mountain
than often assumed . . . The debt 'mountain' is, in part, a mirage,' the
report says.
It warns that the banks' unwillingness to make new loans to the property
industry could hold back the sector's recovery.
'Further reductions in bank lending could inflict additional wounds on the
market and help to hold back values,' it says.
Between the beginning of 1987 and May 1991 loans to property companies rose
from just less than Pounds 10bn to Pounds 40.7bn. This figure fell to Pounds
37.9bn last November.
Including debt extended to the construction industry, the total lent to the
property sector is Pounds 53.4bn.
Bank Finance in the Property Sector: Debt Mountain or Mirage? St Quintin
Research, 33 Cavendish Square, London W1M 9HF. Price on application.
</TEXT>
