<HEADLINE>
FT  13 APR 93 / Patten warns test boycott could hit budgets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN Patten yesterday sharpened his confrontation with teaching unions by
hinting that a boycott of school tests this summer could weaken his hand
with the Treasury in future education spending talks.
The education secretary's remarks, in an interview with the Financial Times,
underlined his determination to resist pressure from unions and some
Conservative MPs for this summer's tests to be suspended pending a review.
A concerted boycott by more than 400,000 teachers of at least some tests,
affecting up to 1.2m pupils in schools everywhere bar Scotland, has moved
closer as two teaching unions said they would ballot members over the tests
for seven, 11 and 14-year-olds, after a third withdrew from testing last
month.
The National Association of Schoolmasters and Union of Women Teachers, which
withdrew last month, is defending its boycott in a legal battle with
London's Wandsworth Council.
Mr Patten's attempt to divide moderate teachers and more radical voices
seemed to be dented by yesterday's refusal by the annual conference of the
largest teaching union, the National Union of Teachers, to discuss an
immediate strike over pay as part of a campaign with railworkers,
firefighters and miners.
Strike action by the NUT over pay is still possible next year.
The conference will today consider whether to hold a second vote on
boycotting appraisals of teachers' performance, used to determine merit pay
rises. On Saturday it voted to ballot members on boycotting national tests.
A summer of exam chaos in schools would undermine Mr Patten's political
career - he has admitted that without tests he would be less able to
withstand Treasury pressure on his department's budget.
Mr Patten did not say whether teachers' pay or school budgets could be
directly affected, but asked: 'How on earth can I argue in the forthcoming
public spending round over education expenditure without the hard
information of improving standards that testing gives?'
The education secretary's confrontational strategy suggests that he believes
many teachers, under pressure from parents, will eventually accept that the
tests, although flawed, should go ahead so that improvements can be made
next year.
Mr Patten stressed the need for testing for 14-year-olds to start this year.
'Recent evidence demonstrates the contemporary tragedy that, of last
summer's 16-year-old school leavers, up to 200,000 went on into the world
still grappling with the English language.'
The NUT yesterday voted to ban classes with more than 30 pupils, or more
than 20 for practical lessons.
The decision by the union's annual conference in Brighton means pupils face
being sent home from class as teachers refuse to take large classes, Mr
Patten was warned.
Editorial Comment, Page 15
</TEXT>
