<HEADLINE>
FT  13 APR 93 / FT Satellite Monitor: Over 3m homes get multi-channel TV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BETWEEN 3m and 3.4m homes in the UK now have access to satellite television,
four years after the launch of Sky Television, the final FT Satellite
Monitor shows.
To mark the 48th and last monthly monitor Continental Research, which
produces it, commissioned two other market research organisations, NOP and
RSGB, to conduct separate surveys of the size of the satellite market.
More than 10,000 interviews were conducted - more than 13,000 if regular
interviewing carried out by BARB, the official television audience
organisation, is included.
In 4,000 telephone interviews last month Continental found that 3.33m
households were receiving satellite television channels by dish, cable or
communal aerial systems.
The RSGB figure from 4,000 face-to-face interviews was 3.37m, and NOP came
up with a total of 2.99m based on 2,000 telephone interviews. BARB's 3,500
face-to-face interviews produced a total of 3.15m.
Continental believes that the best estimate for the total number of homes
which can receive the new channels is 3.24m. This adds up to more than 9m
individuals aged 4 or over, or 17 per cent of the UK population.
Continental has decided to stop publishing monthly changes in the number of
satellite homes because it has become more difficult to measure the figures
accurately as the market has grown.
Mr John Clemens, chairman of Continental Research, said yesterday: 'This
leads to unnecessary controversy about the level of satellite TV
penetration, with the monthly differences (with other market research
groups) being the result of a mix of different definitions and sampling
error.'
Continental will continue to research the number of homes receiving
satellite TV and will publish regular reports.
Its first forecast published in 1988 suggested that there would be 4m
satellite homes by the end of last year. It now believed that the 4m figure
would be reached by the end of this year and that by the 2000 homes
receiving satellite channels would have risen to 9.5m or just over 40 per
cent.
The research group has a data base of 200,000 interviews. They show that
satellite television is mainly geared to 'young large families in the mass
market'.
The market profile shows that 37 per cent of satellite homes come from the
ABC1 social groups, professional and managerial. Skilled workers, the C2Ds,
make up 56 per cent and the poorest and oldest, the Es, 7 per cent.
One in 10 adults says he or she intends to install a dish.
Meanwhile GfK, the marketing services group, today publishes its latest
estimate of the satellite dish market. GfK, which is sponsored by the ITV
Association, estimates that on February 20 a total of 2.098m satellite
dishes had been installed. This represented an increase of 39,000 since its
estimate a month ago.
The GfK survey does not include distribution of satellite channels by cable,
and Northern Ireland, the Isle of Man and the Channel Islands are excluded.
The market research group has also carried out work on 'churn' - those who
get rid of their satellite dishes. Churn totalled 78,000 dishes in the first
half of last year, rising to 142,000 in the second half.
GfK believes between 40 per cent and 50 per cent of those who had BSB
Squarials did not install an Astra dish to continue receiving satellite
television.
</TEXT>
