<HEADLINE>
FT  13 APR 93 / Backing on private cash for hospitals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOSPITALS should be free to use private-sector funding to finance new
facilities, a prominent Tory backbench MP argues in a new paper, David Owen
writes.
Mr David Willetts, the MP for Havant and a member of the influential social
security select committee, makes the suggestion in a wide-ranging
examination of how private funding could be brought into the National Health
Service.
He urges the government to 'be clear' about what sort of ideas it is
prepared to contemplate. 'The political sensitivity surrounding private
provision is much reduced if it is manifestly supplying an extra new
facility,' he says.
Mr Willetts, a former director of studies at the Centre for Policy Studies,
the rightwing think tank, says that the 'crucial' first step in giving
private providers the opportunity to tender for new NHS developments would
be for the Department of Health to liberalise its capital control
pro-cedures.
Past proposals for bringing private finance into the NHS have failed to come
to fruition mainly because of a combination of Treasury rules, political
caution and exaggerated expectations, Mr Willetts says.
The paper was written at the request of the Social Market Foundation, an
independent think tank.
