<HEADLINE>
FT  13 APR 93 / Insider trading comes under Commons scrutiny
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TOUGHER RULES on insider dealing should move a step nearer the statute book
tomorrow when they are due to receive their second Commons reading as part
of a wider ranging criminal justice bill, David Owen writes.
The measure, intended to align UK law with the European Community's insider
dealing directive, would define an 'insider' as anyone who has inside
information as a result of their employment, profession or duties.
The bill has triggered some disquiet in the City, and the government has
indicated it will consider amendments to its proposals where these are
deemed necessary. The areas in which changes are most likely should emerge
during the committee stage which will follow tomorrow's vote.
</TEXT>
