<HEADLINE>
FT  13 APR 93 / Challenge to Vietnam over POWs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GENERAL John Vessey, a special US emissary to Hanoi, will this week push
Vietnam to confirm or deny a newly discovered secret report claiming that
Hanoi held 1,205 US prisoners of war in 1972, more than double the number
returned to the US at the end of the Vietnam war, writes Nancy Dunne in
Washington.
According to Izvestia newspaper, the document was discovered in a search of
former Soviet archives.
The prisoner of war issue has long prevented improved US-Vietnamese
relations. The Clinton administration has been under pressure from business
to renew relations with its former enemy now that it has opened its borders
to investment and trade.
Miss Dee Dee Myers, White House spokeswoman, said relations with Vietnam
could not be normalised until the US was certain Vietnam was doing all it
could to account for Americans missing during the war. Only 591 prisoners
were released.
</TEXT>
