<HEADLINE>
FT  10 APR 93 / Clinton seeks Gatt fast-track extension
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE and ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US administration asked Congress yesterday to move swiftly to grant it
eight more months to complete the Uruguay Round of world trade talks under
an extension of the vital 'fast-track' negotiating authority.
The request would allow President Bill Clinton to notify Congress no later
than December 15 that he intends to enter a Uruguay Round agreement before
April 15 1994. In giving 'fast-track' authority, Congress must vote for or
against a Gatt package as a whole and not try to amend it.
Sir Leon Brittan, EC trade commissioner, said in Brussels: 'This is
excellent news for the Uruguay Round. . . The time allowed is sufficiently
long for the remaining negotiations to take place but sufficiently short for
it to put the necessary pressure on all concerned.'
While the eight-month extension request was expected, there was surprise
that the White House was seeking a 'clean' fast-track bill with no
amendments. Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade representative, had previously
indicated no objection to attaching additional tough 'market-opening'
measures.
But an official said that, 'given the urgency of the Round,' the
administration decided the fast-track request should 'not be encumbered' by
more controversial legislation.
</TEXT>
